# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: retrofit-java-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The **client–server model** is a form of messaging pattern in a distributed application structure that partitions tasks or workloads between the providers of a resource or service, called servers, and service requesters, called clients.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Often clients and servers communicate over a computer network on separate hardware, but both client and server may be on the same device.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] A server host runs one or more server programs, which share their resources with clients.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] A client usually does not share its computing resources, but it requests content or service from a server and may share its own content as part of the request.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Clients, therefore, initiate communication sessions with servers, which await incoming requests.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Examples of computer applications that use the client–server model are email, network printing, and the World Wide Web.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The server component provides a function or service to one or many clients, which initiate requests for such services.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Servers are classified by the services they provide.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] For example, a web server serves web pages and a file server serves computer files.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] A shared resource may be any of the server computer's software and electronic components, from programs and data to processors and storage devices.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The sharing of resources of a server constitutes a *service*.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Whether a computer is a client, a server, or both, is determined by the nature of the application that requires the service functions.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] For example, a single computer can run a web server and file server software at the same time to serve different data to clients making different kinds of requests.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The client software can also communicate with server software within the same computer.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Communication between servers, such as to synchronize data, is sometimes called *inter-server* or *server-to-server* communication.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Generally, a service is an abstraction of computer resources and a client does not have to be concerned with how the server performs while fulfilling the request and delivering the response.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The client only has to understand the response based on the relevant application protocol, i.e. the content and the formatting of the data for the requested service.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Clients and servers exchange messages in a request–response messaging pattern.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The client sends a request, and the server returns a response.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] This exchange of messages is an example of inter-process communication.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] To communicate, the computers must have a common language, and they must follow rules so that both the client and the server know what to expect.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The language and rules of communication are defined in a communications protocol.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] All protocols operate in the application layer.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The application layer protocol defines the basic patterns of the dialogue.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] To formalize the data exchange even further, the server may implement an application programming interface (API).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The API is an abstraction layer for accessing a service.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] By restricting communication to a specific content format, it facilitates parsing.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] By abstracting access, it facilitates cross-platform data exchange.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] A server may receive requests from many distinct clients in a short period.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] A computer can only perform a limited number of tasks at any moment, and relies on a scheduling system to prioritize incoming requests from clients to accommodate them.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] To prevent abuse and maximize availability, the server software may limit the availability to clients.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Denial of service attacks are designed to exploit a server's obligation to process requests by overloading it with excessive request rates.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Encryption should be applied if sensitive information is to be communicated between the client and the server.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] When a bank customer accesses online banking services with a web browser (the client), the client initiates a request to the bank's web server.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The customer's login credentials are compared against a database, and the webserver accesses that database server as a client.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] An application server interprets the returned data by applying the bank's business logic and provides the output to the webserver.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Finally, the webserver returns the result to the client web browser for display.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In each step of this sequence of client–server message exchanges, a computer processes a request and returns data.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] This is the request-response messaging pattern.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] When all the requests are met, the sequence is complete.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] This example illustrates a design pattern applicable to the client–server model: separation of concerns.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Server-side refers to programs and operations that run on the server.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] This is in contrast to client-side programs and operations which run on the client.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] "Server-side software" refers to a computer application, such as a web server, that runs on remote server hardware, reachable from a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Operations may be performed server-side because they require access to information or functionality that is not available on the client, or because performing such operations on the client side would be slow, unreliable, or insecure.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Client and server programs may be commonly available ones such as free or commercial web servers and web browsers, communicating with each other using standardized protocols.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Or, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Server-side operations include both those that are carried out in response to client requests, and non-client-oriented operations such as maintenance tasks.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In a computer security context, server-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on a server computer system, rather than on the client side, or in between the two.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] For example, an attacker might exploit an SQL injection vulnerability in a web application in order to maliciously change or gain unauthorized access to data in the server's database.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might break into a server system using vulnerabilities in the underlying operating system and then be able to access database and other files in the same manner as authorized administrators of the server.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In the case of an Internet-dependent user application like Google Earth, while querying and display of map data takes place on the client side, the server is responsible for permanent storage of map data, resolving user queries into map data to be returned to the client, etc.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Web applications and services can be implemented in almost any language, as long as they can return data to standards-based web browsers (possibly via intermediary programs) in formats which they can use.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Client-side refers to operations that are performed by the client in a computer network.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Typically, a client is a computer application, such as a web browser, that runs on a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device, and connects to a server as necessary.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Additionally, if operations can be performed by the client, without sending data over the network, they may take less time, use less bandwidth, and incur a lesser security risk.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example according to standard protocols such as HTTP or FTP, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (e.g. most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both HTTP and FTP).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be termed client-side operations.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In a computer security context, client-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on the client / user's computer system, rather than on the server side, or in between the two.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] As an example, if a server contained an encrypted file or message which could only be decrypted using a key housed on the user's computer system, a client-side attack would normally be an attacker's only opportunity to gain access to the decrypted contents.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] For instance, the attacker might cause malware to be installed on the client system, allowing the attacker to view the user's screen, record the user's keystrokes, and steal copies of the user's encryption keys, etc.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might employ cross-site scripting vulnerabilities to execute malicious code on the client's system without needing to install any permanently resident malware.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Distributed computing projects such as SETI@home and the Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search, as well as Internet-dependent applications like Google Earth, rely primarily on client-side operations.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] They initiate a connection with the server (either in response to a user query, as with Google Earth, or in an automated fashion, as with SETI@home), and request some data.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The server selects a data set (a server-side operation) and sends it back to the client.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The client then analyzes the data (a client-side operation), and, when the analysis is complete, displays it to the user (as with Google Earth) and/or transmits the results of calculations back to the server (as with SETI@home).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] An early form of client–server architecture is remote job entry, dating at least to OS/360 (announced 1964), where the request was to run a job, and the response was the output.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] While formulating the client–server model in the 1960s and 1970s, computer scientists building ARPANET (at the Stanford Research Institute) used the terms *server-host* (or *serving host*) and *user-host* (or *using-host*), and these appear in the early documents RFC 5 and RFC 4.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] This usage was continued at Xerox PARC in the mid-1970s.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] One context in which researchers used these terms was in the design of a computer network programming language called Decode-Encode Language (DEL).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The purpose of this language was to accept commands from one computer (the user-host), which would return status reports to the user as it encoded the commands in network packets.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Another DEL-capable computer, the server-host, received the packets, decoded them, and returned formatted data to the user-host.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] A DEL program on the user-host received the results to present to the user.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Development of DEL was just beginning in 1969, the year that the United States Department of Defense established ARPANET (predecessor of Internet).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] An early use of the word *client* occurs in "Separating Data from Function in a Distributed File System", a 1978 paper by Xerox PARC computer scientists Howard Sturgis, James Mitchell, and Jay Israel.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The authors are careful to define the term for readers, and explain that they use it to distinguish between the user and the user's network node (the client).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] By 1992, the word *server* had entered into general parlance.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The client-server model does not dictate that server-hosts must have more resources than client-hosts.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Rather, it enables any general-purpose computer to extend its capabilities by using the shared resources of other hosts.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Centralized computing, however, specifically allocates a large number of resources to a small number of computers.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The more computation is offloaded from client-hosts to the central computers, the simpler the client-hosts can be.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] It relies heavily on network resources (servers and infrastructure) for computation and storage.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] A diskless node loads even its operating system from the network, and a computer terminal has no operating system at all; it is only an input/output interface to the server.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In contrast, a rich client, such as a personal computer, has many resources and does not rely on a server for essential functions.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] As microcomputers decreased in price and increased in power from the 1980s to the late 1990s, many organizations transitioned computation from centralized servers, such as mainframes and minicomputers, to rich clients.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] This afforded greater, more individualized dominion over computer resources, but complicated information technology management.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] During the 2000s, web applications matured enough to rival application software developed for a specific microarchitecture.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] This maturation, more affordable mass storage, and the advent of service-oriented architecture were among the factors that gave rise to the cloud computing trend of the 2010s.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In addition to the client-server model, distributed computing applications often use the peer-to-peer (P2P) application architecture.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In the client-server model, the server is often designed to operate as a centralized system that serves many clients.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] The computing power, memory and storage requirements of a server must be scaled appropriately to the expected workload.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Load-balancing and failover systems are often employed to scale the server beyond a single physical machine.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Load balancing is defined as the methodical and efficient distribution of network or application traffic across multiple servers in a server farm.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Each load balancer sits between client devices and backend servers, receiving and then distributing incoming requests to any available server capable of fulfilling them.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In a peer-to-peer network, two or more computers (*peers*) pool their resources and communicate in a decentralized system.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Peers are coequal, or equipotent nodes in a non-hierarchical network.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Unlike clients in a client-server or client-queue-client network, peers communicate with each other directly.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] In peer-to-peer networking, an algorithm in the peer-to-peer communications protocol balances load, and even peers with modest resources can help to share the load.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] If a node becomes unavailable, its shared resources remain available as long as other peers offer it.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Ideally, a peer does not need to achieve high availability because other, redundant peers make up for any resource downtime; as the availability and load capacity of peers change, the protocol reroutes requests.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/client-server-model] Both client-server and master-slave are regarded as sub-categories of distributed peer-to-peer systems.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/interface-description-language] An **interface description language** or **interface definition language** (**IDL**) is a generic term for a language that lets a program or object written in one language communicate with another program written in an unknown language.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are usually used to describe data types and interfaces in a language-independent way, for example, between those written in C++ and those written in Java.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are commonly used in remote procedure call software.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/interface-description-language] In these cases the machines at either end of the *link* may be using different operating systems and computer languages.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs offer a bridge between the two different systems.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] In the Java computer programming language, an **annotation** is a form of syntactic metadata that can be added to Java source code, like an attribute.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Classes, methods, variables, parameters and Java packages may be annotated.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Like Javadoc tags, Java annotations can be read from source files.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Unlike Javadoc tags, Java annotations can also be embedded in and read from Java class files generated by the Java compiler.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] This allows annotations to be retained by the Java virtual machine at run-time and read via reflection.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] It is possible to create meta-annotations out of the existing ones in Java.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] The Java platform has various *ad-hoc* annotation mechanisms—for example, the *`transient`* modifier, or the *`@Deprecated`* javadoc tag.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] The Java Specification Request JSR-175 introduced the general-purpose annotation (also known as *metadata*) facility to the Java Community Process in 2002; it gained approval in September 2004.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotations became available in the language itself beginning with version 1.5 of the Java Development Kit (JDK).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] The `apt` tool provided a provisional interface for compile-time annotation processing in JDK version 1.5; JSR-269 formalized this, and it became integrated into the javac compiler in version 1.6.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] In C++26, C++ added annotations for reflection that are similar to Java annotations.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Java defines a set of annotations that are built into the language.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Of the seven standard annotations, three are part of java.lang, and the remaining four are imported from `java.lang.annotation`.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] There was previously an annotation, `@ManagedBean`, located in `jakarta.annotation`, which was historically used to declare a Managed Bean which are container managed objects that support a small set of basic services such as resource injection, lifecycle callbacks and interceptors.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] This example demonstrates the use of the `@Override` annotation.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] It instructs the compiler to check parent classes for matching methods.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] In this case, an error is generated because the `gettype()` method of class Cat doesn't in fact override `getType()` of class Animal like is desired, because of the mismatching case.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] If the `@Override` annotation were absent, a new method of name `gettype()` would be created in class Cat.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotation type declarations are similar to normal interface declarations.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] An at-sign (@) precedes the keyword "interface".
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotations may include a set of key-value pairs, which are modeled as methods of the annotation type.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Each method declaration defines an element of the annotation type.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Method declarations must not have any parameters or a throws clause.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Return types are restricted to primitives, String, Class, enums, annotations, and arrays of the preceding types.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] The compiler reserves a set of special annotations (including `@Deprecated`, `@Override` and `@SuppressWarnings`) for syntactic purposes.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Annotations are widely used by frameworks as a way of conveniently applying behaviors to user-defined classes and methods that must otherwise be declared in an external source (such as an XML configuration file) or programmatically (with API calls).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] For instance, the library *Project Lombok* makes extensive usage of annotations to reduce boilerplate.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] The annotations are not method calls and will not, by themselves, do anything.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Rather, the class object is passed to the Jakarta Persistence implementation at run-time, which then extracts the annotations to generate an object–relational mapping.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] When Java source code is compiled, annotations can be processed by compiler plug-ins called annotation processors.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Processors can produce informational messages or create additional Java source files or resources, which in turn may be compiled and processed.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] However, annotation processors cannot modify the annotated code itself.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] (Code modifications may be implemented using methods beyond the Java Language Specification.) The Java compiler conditionally stores annotation metadata in the class files, if the annotation has a `RetentionPolicy` of `CLASS` or `RUNTIME`.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Later, the JVM or other programs can look for the metadata to determine how to interact with the program elements or change their behavior.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] In addition to processing an annotation using an annotation processor, a Java programmer can write their own code that uses reflection to process the annotation.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Java SE 5 supports a new interface that is defined in the `java.lang.reflect` package.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] This package contains the interface called `AnnotatedElement` that is implemented by the Java reflection classes including `Class`, `Constructor`, `Field`, `Method`, and `Package`.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] The implementations of this interface are used to represent an annotated element of the program currently running in the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] This interface allows annotations to be read reflectively.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] The `AnnotatedElement` interface provides access to annotations having `RUNTIME` retention.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] This access is provided by the `getAnnotation`, `getAnnotations`, and `isAnnotationPresent` methods.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Because annotation types are compiled and stored in byte code files just like classes, the annotations returned by these methods can be queried just like any regular Java object.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-annotation] Libraries such as JUnit use annotation processing to generate unit tests.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:retrofit-java-lib/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
